		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30707917">Interestingly, sequels have been a big thing on almost every industry (Film, games, books, etc). They are mainly used in two different aspects. Either they want to continue a story that they left off, whether it is from an adapted source or not, and try to satisfy the audience in offering a developed sequel that could be just as or even better than the prequel, or they just want to bank off from the hype of the prequel and make it half-assed. <br />
<br />
It goes to show that the industry doesn't really want to make new shows from a manga or not because it doesn't offer up a profit for their financial assets. The other obvious reason is just the fact that it's easier to market a sequel than make a new show as you can see if you see the development process of selling a show to an executive. In an optimistic sense, the sequels that will sell billions of profit can be used to make sure that those original works can be financially feasible for them to make and can ensure that they won't have any trouble even if it flops.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><div style="text-align: center;"><!--link--><a href="http://gonzonyan.wordpress.com/" rel="nofollow"><img class="userimg" data-src="http://i.minus.com/iFBKqTvDcfeI1.png" /></a><!--center--></div></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
