		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30714945">It would seem the typical length of TV series has sharply reduced, and thus the number of sequels increased. I guess part of the reason is that the medium became more crowded and harder to break through, but making anime overall is a riskier venture than it used to, so gathering enough funding for more than one or two cour at once is probably challenging. <br />
<br />
Though this production model might be partly responsible for the number of anime that lack satisfying endings, it probably can also be thanked for the likes of Kaiba, Bartender, NHK or Casshern Sins which initially sold &lt;800 copies per volume and might never break even. "Mass-producing short series and continuing whatever makes a profit" at least allowed a few unprofitable gems to be made.<br />
<br />
As for the question of "noteworthy" anime being sequels, or as I call them "continuation of bluechip franchises" (since we might as well include things like Mine Fujiko, Rebuild or Sailor Moon on top of sequels like Natsume, Hidamari etc.), I don't know if there's been a temporary creativity low in 2012 and 2013 or if it's a false impression but one thing we did find in C&amp;C is that the "early 00s" had a lot more noteworthy non-sequel anime than the current years. I wonder if Lindle remembers the exact years as I think he was the one to highlight this period when we were debating decades.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
