		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30719263">The anime industry has, for most of its history, been beholden to "safe bets."  For a long time, this has meant adapting popular manga (in recent years there's been a trend toward adapting light novels and visual novels as well) and relying on the strength of existing brands to move a certain minimum number of copies.The anime industry's dependence on "safe bets" is mostly based on the risk associated with these ventures.<br />
<br />
The finances that drive anime production have changed in the past few decades. The production costs associated with anime have decreased over time, especially with the advent of digital anime and techniques like digital interpolation.  Otaku superconsumerism has also made it possible for anime productions to achieve financial success with less market penetration.  It used to be that VHS tapes with several episodes would sell for $100 a pop because the target market was video rental stores.  Now, there are people who buy blu-rays for similar prices simply because they are enthusiast consumers.<br />
<br />
One of the results of this is that the amount of anime produced over time has increased.  The numbers posted by Lindle above reflect this pretty well.  In 2009, 117 anime were produced.  By 2013, that number had increased to 181.<br />
<br />
Conversely, the manga market has been shrinking in recent years.  The growth of anime combined with the commercial decline of manga has had the end result of producing increasingly large generations of "anime natives."  It used to be that if you wanted to sell anime, you had to target manga readers.  Now, to sell anime, you target existing anime fans.  And how do you sell to existing anime fans?  Evidently, the answer is "sequels."</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
