		<tr>
		  <td width="135" class="forum_boardrow2" style="border-width: 0px 0px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="messageuser30720347" style="padding-bottom: 2px;"><a href="/profile/Kuiper"><strong>Kuiper</strong></a></div>
		  
		  <a href="/profile/Kuiper"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/useravatars/331692.png" vspace="2" border="0"></a>
		  <br>
		  Offline<br>
		  Joined: May 2010<br>
		  Posts: 74
		  </td>
		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30720347">To expand on Gonzo's point (and perhaps stating the obvious), but anime that exist unto themselves beg continuation more than anime that exist to publicize the existence of a long-running manga series.  For example, Berserk ends after 25 episodes, essentially with the message that if you want to find out what happens next, you should go read the manga.  But what about cases where there is no source material to point viewers back to?  For the story to continue, an anime sequel is necessary.<br />
<br />
That being said, I believe that original works aren't wholly responsible for the increase in sequels.  For example, last year's Ore no Imouto, the various *Monogatari anime, Highschool DxD, and Infinite Stratos are all sequels and adaptive works.<br />
<br />
Looking at all of these examples, what do they have in common?  They're all light novel adaptations.<br />
<br />
I think the case here is not that "go back to the source material to see the rest of the story" doesn't exist, but rather that much of the audience for the anime has no interest in the source material because people like visual media, and light novels don't scratch that same itch in the way that manga can.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
